default3.1 
defaultPeople with long term conditions interact with the health service in a different way than those with a single episode of care, such as a broken leg. 
defaultThose with long term conditions will have more frequent contact with the NHS, often
default interacting with multiple
default parts of the system
default over a sustained period of time
default. 
defaultGiven many long term conditions cannot be "cured", the focus 
defaultwill be more
default 
defaulton
default managing the condition
default and helping people 
defaultto 
defaultstay as well as possible for as long as possible
default. 
default&#xa0;
default3.2 
defaultThis all means that the health service needs to interact in a different way 
defaultwith patients th
defaulta
defaultn in the past 
defaultand a key part of this will be to ensure that the various 
defaultparts of the system are joined up to ensure that the patients' interactions with the system (or 'care pathway') are properly coordinated. This approach needs to make better use of resources and improve people's experiences by delivering the right care in the right place. This greater integration of care
default needs to involve not just NHS services but also local authority provision, particularly social care
default. It also means engaging better with patients as people with an active role to play in improving and maintaining their own health, not simply passive recipients of care. 
defaultWe welcome the 
defaultnarrative
default for integrated care
default recently
default set out by National Voices, which is helpful in setting out what is meant by the term integration
default and the recent announcement by the Government on integration 'pioneer' sites. 
